{
  "text": "Therefore, the process S experiences larger fluctuations the closer the value m(\u03bd) is to 1. On the other hand, m(\u03bd) = 0 occurs in the absence of the trend chasing speculators. In this case, or with the value m(\u03bd) close to zero, the fluctuations are of a similar size as in the standard Black-Scholes model. In other words, the presence of the trend chasing speculators makes the market more risky, and leads to greater fluctuations. This is similar to findings of DeLong, Shleifer, Summers and Waldman [CITATION_1] , in which the presence of noise traders increases the risk for informed investors. If m(\u03bd) > 1 then combining Theorem 3.1 and Theorem 3.3 implies",
